[[File:Right Livelihood Award 2009-award ceremony-1.jpg|thumb|The award ceremony in the [[Riksdag building|Riksdag of Sweden]] in 2009]]
[[File:Right Livelihood Award 2009-award ceremony-7.jpg|thumb|The 2009 award is presented to [[David Suzuki]] by [[Jakob von Uexkull]] (right) and European Commissioner [[Margot Wallström]] (left)]]

The '''Right Livelihood Award''' is an international award to "honour and support those offering practical and exemplary answers to the most urgent challenges facing us today."<ref name="MFA"/> The prize was established in 1980 by [[Germans|German]]-Swedish [[philanthropist]] [[Jakob von Uexkull]], and is presented annually in early December.<ref>Jawetz, Pincas. [http://www.sustainabilitank.info/2009/10/13/the-alternate-nobels-right-livelihood-awards-2009-also-announced-by-sweden/ 30th Right Livelihood Awards: Wake-up calls to secure our common future.] ''SustainabiliTank.'' 13 Oct. 2009.</ref> An international jury, invited by the five regular Right Livelihood Award board members, decides the awards in such fields as [[environmentalism|environmental protection]], [[human rights]], [[sustainable development]], [[health]], [[education]], and [[peace]].<ref name="Thorpe" /> The prize money is shared among the winners, usually numbering four, and is [[Euro|EUR]] 200,000.<ref name=about>[http://www.rightlivelihood.org/award.html About the Right Livelihood Award] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110811061052/http://www.rightlivelihood.org/award.html |date=2011-08-11 }}. Accessed October 26, 2010.</ref> Very often one of the four laureates receives an honorary award, which means that the other three share the prize money.<ref name="Thorpe"/>

Although it is promoted as an '''"Alternative Nobel Prize"''',<ref name="BBC-7647718">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/7647718.stm |title= Indians win 'alternative Nobel' |last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |date= 2 October 2008 |work= |publisher=BBC |accessdate=22 March 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dw-world.de/dw/article/0,2144,3683051,00.html |title= Peace and Social Justice Workers Receive Alternative Nobel Prize |last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |date= 1 October 2008 |work= |publisher=[[Deutsche Welle]] |accessdate=12 June 2017}}</ref><ref name="TheLocal">{{cite web |url=http://www.thelocal.se/29344/20100930/ |title= Global activists honoured with 'Alternative Nobel' prize |last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |date= 30 September 2010 |work=[[The Local]] |publisher= |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101002043224/https://www.thelocal.se/29344/20100930/ |archivedate=2 October 2010|accessdate=12 June 2017}}</ref><ref name="BBC-11445709">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-11445709 |title= Israeli doctors' group wins 'alternative' Nobel prize |last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |date= 30 September 2010 |work= |publisher=BBC |accessdate=22 March 2011}}</ref><ref name="FAZ">{{cite web |url=http://www.faz.net/s/RubBF80E0BCB9BE4D30B11BB6D4CFBD637E/Doc~E2D25260C587C4598BA448B223C540BEC~ATpl~Ecommon~Scontent.html |title= Alternativer Nobelpreis: Kampf gegen Klimawandel, Armut, Kriege ausgezeichnet |last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |date= 13 October 2009 |work= |publisher=[[Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung]] |accessdate=22 March 2011}}</ref> it is not a [[Nobel prize]] (i.e., a prize created by [[Alfred Nobel]]). It does not have any organizational ties to the awarding institutions of the Nobel Prize or the Nobel Foundation.

However, the Right Livelihood Award is sometimes popularly associated with the Nobel prizes; the Right Livelihood Award committee arranged for awards to be made in the [[Riksdag building|Riksdag of Sweden]] the day before the Nobel prizes and the economics prize are also awarded in [[Stockholm]], and the awards are understood as a critique of the traditional Nobel prizes.<ref name="FAZ"/> The establishment of the award followed a failed attempt to have the Nobel Foundation create new prizes in the areas of environmental protection, sustainable development and human rights. The prize has been awarded to a diverse group of people and organisations, including [[Wangari Maathai]], [[Astrid Lindgren]], [[Bianca Jagger]], [[Mordechai Vanunu]], [[Leopold Kohr]], [[Arna Mer-Khamis]], [[Felicia Langer]], [[Petra Kelly]], [[Survival International]], [[Amy Goodman]], [[Memorial (society)|Memorial]], and [[Edward Snowden]].

==Ceremony==
Since 1985, the ceremony has taken place in [[Stockholm]]'s old Parliament building, in the days before the traditional Nobel prizes are awarded in the same city. A group of Swedish Parliamentarians from different parties host the ceremony; in 2009 European Commissioner [[Margot Wallström]] co-hosted the ceremony. However, in 2014 when it became public that one of the recipients of the 2014 prize was [[whistleblower]] [[Edward Snowden]], the ceremonial group was disinvited from the Ministry for Foreign Affairs building in Stockholm.<ref>{{cite news|title=Edward Snowden inte välkommen till UD|url=http://www.aftonbladet.se/nyheter/article19588815.ab|accessdate=24 September 2014|work=Aftonbladet|publisher=Aftonbladet|date=24 September 2014|ref=16}}</ref>

==Nature of the award==
Some media refer to the prize as the ''Alternative Nobel Prize'',<ref name=Thorpe>{{cite book|last1=Thorpe|first1=Edgar|last2=Thorpe|first2=Showick|title=Guide to the Combined Defence Services Exam|publisher=Pearson Education|location=New Delhi|isbn=81-317-0074-7|page=26|chapter=General Awareness: Right Livelihood Award}}</ref> and the prize is frequently understood as a critique of the traditional Nobel prizes.<ref name="FAZ"/>

The prize differs significantly from the [[Nobel Prize]]s:
*it is not a fulfillment of [[Alfred Nobel]]'s bequest and thus not one of Nobel's own prizes;
*it has an open nomination process (anyone can nominate anyone else, except close relatives or their own organizations);<ref>[http://www.rightlivelihood.org/propose_a_candidate.html Right Livelihood Award: Proposals & Selection Process]. Accessed January 24, 2010.</ref>
*it is not limited to specific categories;<ref name=about/>
*the prize money is considerably lower than that of the Nobel Prize. Currently it is €200,000 compared to about €1,000,000 for a Nobel Prize;
*the funds for the prizes now come from donations<ref name="MFA">{{cite web |url=http://www.government.se/sb/d/17191/a/225032 |title=The 2013 Right Livelihood Laureates announced |author=Ministry for Foreign Affairs |format= |pages= |date=26 September 2013 |accessdate=2014-08-14 |quote= |publisher=Government Offices of Sweden |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140303235727/http://www.government.se/sb/d/17191/a/225032 |archivedate=3 March 2014 |df= }}</ref> while the Nobel Prizes come from the revenue of Alfred Nobel's fortune. The [[Nobel Memorial Prize in Economic Sciences]] (which is technically not a Nobel Prize) is financed by the [[Sveriges Riksbank]].

==History==
[[File:Rightlivelihoodaward.jpg|thumb|right|150 px|The 1994 award given to [[Hanumappa Sudarshan|Dr. Sudarshan]] photographed in [[BR Hills]]]]
Jakob von&nbsp;Uexküll, the philatelist, sold his company to create a prize,<ref name="MFA"/> realizing one million US&nbsp;dollars which provided the initial funding of the award. Before establishing the award in 1980, von&nbsp;Uexkull had tried to interest the [[Nobel Foundation]] in new prizes to be awarded together with the Nobel Prizes. He suggested the establishment of two new prizes, one for ecology and one for development.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://rightlivelihood.org/history.html |title=Right Livelihood Award: History - Setting up the 'Alternative Nobel Prize' |publisher=Rightlivelihood.org |date= |accessdate=2012-07-28 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120829121254/http://www.rightlivelihood.org/history.html |archivedate=2012-08-29 |df= }}</ref> Like the [[Sveriges Riksbank Prize in Economic Sciences in Memory of Alfred Nobel|Nobel Economics Prize]], this would have been possible with an amendment to the Nobel Foundation statutes and funding of the prize amount completely separate from Nobel's fortune. The Nobel Prize amount was 880,000 Swedish kronor at that time,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nobelprize.org/nobel_prizes/about/amounts.html |title=The Nobel Prize Amounts |publisher=Nobelprize.org |date= |accessdate=2012-07-28}}</ref> which corresponded to 195,000 US&nbsp;dollars.<ref>[http://currate.com/historical-exchange-rates.php according to historical exchange rate from]</ref> However, as a result of the debate that followed the establishment of the [[Sveriges Riksbank Prize in Economic Sciences in Memory of Alfred Nobel]] (first awarded in 1969), the Nobel Foundation had decided not to associate the Nobel Prize with any additional awards, so von&nbsp;Uexküll's proposal was rejected.<ref name="ttdn">TT-DN (2003-10-02). ''Alternativt Nobelpris delas på fem''. Dagens Nyheter, "Publicerat 2003-10-02 10:08". Retrieved from http://www.dn.se/DNet/jsp/polopoly.jsp?a=188389. {{sv icon}}</ref>

Since 1980, the foundation has presented, as of 2013, awards to 153 Laureates from 64 countries.<ref name="MFA"/> Its self-described purpose is to bestow prizes and thus publicize the work of recipients' local solutions to worldwide problems.<ref>[http://www.rightlivelihood.org/history.html Right Livelihood Award history] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100620110022/http://rightlivelihood.org/history.html |date=2010-06-20 }}</ref>

