[[File:Pectin.jpg|thumb|right|[[Pectin]] is used as a stabiliser in foods such as [[yogurt]]]] A '''stabiliser''' is an [[food additive|additive]] to food which helps to preserve its structure. Typical uses include preventing oil , water [[emulsion]]s from separating in products such as salad dressing; preventing ice crystals from forming in frozen food such as ice cream; and preventing fruit from settling in products such as jam, yoghurt and jellys. The following [[hydrocolloid]]s are the most common ones used as stabilisers:<ref>{{citation |title=Food Stabilisers, Thickeners and Gelling Agents |author=Alan Imeson |publisher=John Wiley & Sons |year=2011 |isbn=978-1-4443-6033-2}}</ref>
*[[alginate]] *[[agar]] *[[carrageen]] *[[cellulose]] and cellulose derivatives *[[gelatin]] *[[guar gum]] *[[gum Arabic]] *[[locust bean gum]] *[[pectin]] *[[starch]] *[[xanthan gum]]
