{{Infobox central bank | bank_name_in_local = | image_1 = Seal of the United States Federal Reserve System.svg | image_title_1 = Seal | image_2 = Federal Reserve.jpg | image_title_2 = The Federal Reserve System [[Eccles Building]] (Headquarters) | headquarters = [[Washington, D.C.]] | president = [[Janet Yellen]] | leader_title = [[Chairman of the Federal Reserve|Chairman]] | bank_of = [[United States]] | currency = [[United States dollar|U.S. dollar]] | currency_iso = USD | borrowing_rate = 2.25% | deposit_rate = 3.5% | website = [http://www.federalreserve.gov/ federalreserve.gov] | footnotes = }}
The '''Term Securities Lending Facility''' (TSLF) is a 28-day facility managed by the [[United States]] [[Federal Reserve]] that offers Treasury general collateral (GC) (i.e., Treasury bills, notes, bonds and inflation-indexed securities) to the [[primary dealer]]s in exchange for other program-eligible collateral. It is intended to promote liquidity in the financing markets for Treasury and other collateral and thus to foster the functioning of financial markets more generally.
This is different from the [[System Open Market Account]] (SOMA) Securities Lending program which offers specific Treasury securities held by SOMA for loan against Treasury GC on an overnight basis. Dealers bid competitively in a multiple-price auction held every day at noon. The TSLF offers Treasury GC held by SOMA for a 28-day term. Dealers bid competitively in single-price auctions held weekly and borrowers will pledge program-eligible collateral.
==History==
TSLF was announced on 11 March 2008.<ref>http://federalreserve.gov/newsevents/press/monetary/20080311a.htm</ref> By the end of the program it loaned out U.S. Treasury securities worth $2.3 trillion to just eighteen Wall Street banks.<ref>Wilson, Linus, Wu, Yan and Prejean, Stephanie, March 21, 2012, "Are the Bailouts of Wall Street Complements or Substitutes?", SSRN Working Paper, Accessed online on April 25, 2012, at http://ssrn.com/abstract=2026988.</ref> In 2008, as liquidity in the global markets came to a halt, the FED took action to allow the TSLF to expand the types of acceptable collateral: student loans, car loans, home equity loans and credit card debt, as long as it was highly rated.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/05/03/business/03fed.html | work=The New York Times | first=Steven R. | last=Weisman | title=Fed Moves to Loosen Tight Credit | date=3 May 2008}}</ref> Ironically, many of the establishment rating firms were themselves shown to be of little worth in the preceding few years, and the ratings system was in the state of being [[Subprime mortgage crisis#Role of credit rating agencies|reworked]].
The collateral for the Term Securities Lending Facility (TSLF) also has been expanded; eligible collateral will now include all investment-grade debt securities. Previously, only Treasury securities, agency securities, and AAA-rated mortgage-backed and asset-backed securities could be pledged.<ref name="Federal Reserve Bank of New York">{{cite web|title=Term Securities Lending Facility: Programs Terms and Conditions - Federal Reserve Bank of New York|url=http://www.newyorkfed.org/markets/tslf_terms.html|accessdate=6 November 2011}}</ref> This was one of many [[emergency lending]] programs of the [[Federal Reserve]] during the [[Financial crisis of 2008-2009]].
